Water Quality Prediction Analysis

What is water quality?

Water quality refers to the chemical, physical, and biological characteristics of water based on the standards of its usage.

Management of water quality is a real-world issue !!

Over time, there has been increasing recognition of the importance of drinking water quality and its impact on public health. This has led to increasing protection and management of water quality.

What is potability?

Potable water, or water suitable for human consumption, is water that can be used for drinking, cooking, hygiene, and other household chores.

Aim of Project

This project aims to find the best-fit model to predict the water potability based on a dataset which contains water quality metrics for 3276 different water bodies.

The goal is to correctly classify water samples as potable (1) or not potable (0).

Applying GridSearchCV on 6 algorithms to find the best model

Algorithms used are as follow:

  • Logistic Regression
  • Decision Tree Classifier
  • Random Forest Classifier
  • K-Nearest Neighbours
  • SVM
  • XGBoost

For each algorithm we will train the model on training data and test its accuracy of prediction when tested on testing data.

Finally, we will compare the accuracy of various models used.

In[49]:
# splitting into training & testing data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=0)
In[50]:
# importing necessary libraries
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from xgboost import XGBClassifier

Logistic Regression

In[51]:
clf = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial', max_iter=500), {'C':[1,5,10,15]}, cv=5)
clf.fit(X_train,y_train)
clf.best_score_

Conclusion

XGBoost has highest accuracy among the 6 algorithms. Hence, XGBoost is best model for water quality prediction for this dataset.
